"use strict";(globalThis.webpackChunkdocs=globalThis.webpackChunkdocs||[]).push([[2434],{236:e=>{e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"welcome","metadata":{"permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/welcome","editUrl":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/tree/master/docs/blog/2021-08-26-welcome/index.md","source":"@site/blog/2021-08-26-welcome/index.md","title":"Physical AI & Humanoid Robotics Textbook","description":"Welcome to the official textbook and documentation hub for the Physical AI and Humanoid Robotics course! \ud83d\ude80","date":"2021-08-26T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"robotics","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/robotics"},{"inline":true,"label":"ai","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/ai"},{"inline":true,"label":"physical-ai","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/physical-ai"},{"inline":true,"label":"course","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/course"}],"readingTime":0.59,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Iqra Naz (Course Author)","title":"Lead Instructor, Physical AI & Humanoid Robotics","url":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421","page":{"permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/authors/iqra-naz-421"},"socials":{"linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/iqra-naz-linkedin/","github":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421"},"imageURL":"img/new-removebg-preview.png","key":"IqraNaz421"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"welcome","title":"Physical AI & Humanoid Robotics Textbook","authors":["IqraNaz421"],"tags":["robotics","ai","physical-ai","course"]},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Implementing Basic Control Loops in Python (MDX Tutorial)","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/mdx-blog-post"}},"content":"**Welcome to the official textbook and documentation hub for the Physical AI and Humanoid Robotics course!** \ud83d\ude80\\n\\nThis platform serves as a comprehensive resource, providing in-depth chapters, practical tutorials, and the latest research in the field of intelligent robotic systems.\\n\\n### What You Will Find Here\\n\\n* **\ud83d\udcd8 Comprehensive Chapters:** Explore detailed theoretical concepts of physical AI, control systems, sensing, and actuation.\\n* **\ud83d\udee0\ufe0f Hands-on Tutorials:** Follow step-by-step guides on implementing AI algorithms on robotic platforms.\\n* **\ud83c\udf10 Latest Research:** Stay updated with the rapidly evolving world of humanoid robotics.\\n\\n**We encourage you to use the built-in search and chat features** for quick answers to your queries as you navigate through the material.\\n\\nLet\'s build the future of robotics together!"},{"id":"mdx-blog-post","metadata":{"permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/mdx-blog-post","editUrl":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/tree/master/docs/blog/2021-08-01-mdx-blog-post.mdx","source":"@site/blog/2021-08-01-mdx-blog-post.mdx","title":"Implementing Basic Control Loops in Python (MDX Tutorial)","description":"This interactive post guides you through setting up a basic Proportional-Integral-Derivative (PID) control loop in Python, a core concept in robotics. We\'ll use MDX to embed runnable code and notes.","date":"2021-08-01T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"tutorial","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/tutorial"},{"inline":true,"label":"python","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/python"},{"inline":true,"label":"control-systems","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/control-systems"},{"inline":true,"label":"actuators","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/actuators"}],"readingTime":0.88,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Iqra Naz (Course Author)","title":"Lead Instructor, Physical AI & Humanoid Robotics","url":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421","page":{"permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/authors/iqra-naz-421"},"socials":{"linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/iqra-naz-linkedin/","github":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421"},"imageURL":"img/new-removebg-preview.png","key":"IqraNaz421"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"mdx-blog-post","title":"Implementing Basic Control Loops in Python (MDX Tutorial)","authors":["IqraNaz421"],"tags":["tutorial","python","control-systems","actuators"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Physical AI & Humanoid Robotics Textbook","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/welcome"},"nextItem":{"title":"Deep Dive into Kinematics and Control Systems for Humanoids","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/long-blog-post"}},"content":"**This interactive post guides you through setting up a basic Proportional-Integral-Derivative (PID) control loop in Python, a core concept in robotics.** We\'ll use MDX to embed runnable code and notes.\\n\\n:::tip Prerequisites\\nAapko Python ki basic understanding aur Thori si Linear Algebra ki knowledge honi chahiye.\\n:::\\n\\n### 1. PID Controller ka Nazariya (Theory)\\n\\nPID Controller ka kaam **measured value** aur **desired setpoint** ke beech ka farq (error) kam karna hota hai. Yeh teen term use karta hai: Proportional (P), Integral (I), aur Derivative (D). \\n\\n[Image of a PID control loop diagram]\\n\\n\\n### 2. Python mein PID Class\\n\\nAaiye, hum ek basic Python class banate hain.\\n\\n```python\\n# PIDController.py\\nclass PIDController:\\n    def __init__(self, Kp, Ki, Kd, dt):\\n        self.Kp = Kp  # Proportional gain\\n        self.Ki = Ki  # Integral gain\\n        self.Kd = Kd  # Derivative gain\\n        self.dt = dt  # Time step\\n\\n        self.previous_error = 0\\n        self.integral = 0\\n\\n    def calculate_output(self, setpoint, measured_value):\\n        error = setpoint - measured_value\\n\\n        # Proportional Term\\n        P = self.Kp * error\\n\\n        # Integral Term\\n        self.integral += error * self.dt\\n        I = self.Ki * self.integral\\n\\n        # Derivative Term\\n        derivative = (error - self.previous_error) / self.dt\\n        D = self.Kd * derivative\\n\\n        # Total Output\\n        output = P + I + D\\n        self.previous_error = error\\n        return output"},{"id":"long-blog-post","metadata":{"permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/long-blog-post","editUrl":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/tree/master/docs/blog/2019-05-29-long-blog-post.md","source":"@site/blog/2019-05-29-long-blog-post.md","title":"Deep Dive into Kinematics and Control Systems for Humanoids","description":"This post provides a technical deep dive into the foundational principles of Kinematics and Control Systems\u2014the backbone of any functional humanoid robot. Without precise control over movement, advanced AI is meaningless in a physical body.","date":"2019-05-29T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"kinematics","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/kinematics"},{"inline":true,"label":"control-theory","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/control-theory"},{"inline":true,"label":"robotics-fundamentals","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/robotics-fundamentals"},{"inline":true,"label":"actuators","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/actuators"}],"readingTime":1.9,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Iqra Naz (Course Author)","title":"Lead Instructor, Physical AI & Humanoid Robotics","url":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421","page":{"permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/authors/iqra-naz-421"},"socials":{"linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/iqra-naz-linkedin/","github":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421"},"imageURL":"img/new-removebg-preview.png","key":"IqraNaz421"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"long-blog-post","title":"Deep Dive into Kinematics and Control Systems for Humanoids","authors":["IqraNaz421"],"tags":["kinematics","control-theory","robotics-fundamentals","actuators"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Implementing Basic Control Loops in Python (MDX Tutorial)","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/mdx-blog-post"},"nextItem":{"title":"The Dawn of Physical AI - Why it Matters Now","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/first-blog-post"}},"content":"**This post provides a technical deep dive into the foundational principles of Kinematics and Control Systems\u2014the backbone of any functional humanoid robot.** Without precise control over movement, advanced AI is meaningless in a physical body.\\n\\n### Understanding Kinematics\\n\\nKinematics deals with the **geometry of motion** without considering the forces that cause the motion. For a multi-jointed robot arm or a walking humanoid leg, we must calculate the relationship between joint angles and the end-effector\'s position in space.\\n\\n* **Forward Kinematics:** Calculating the position and orientation of the end-effector given all joint angles. This is relatively straightforward.\\n* **Inverse Kinematics (IK):** Calculating the required joint angles to place the end-effector at a desired position and orientation. This is complex, often involving non-linear equations and multiple solutions. Advanced humanoid movement relies heavily on solving IK problems rapidly.\\n\\n### The Role of Control Systems\\n\\nControl systems ensure the robot executes the desired movement accurately and safely, despite disturbances (like gravity or external forces).\\n\\n#### 1. PID Control\\n\\nThe **Proportional-Integral-Derivative (PID)** controller is the most common feedback loop used in low-level motor control. It continuously calculates an error value as the difference between a desired setpoint (e.g., target joint angle) and a measured process variable (actual joint angle). \\n\\n[Image of PID control loop diagram]\\n\\n\\n* **Proportional (P):** Responds to the current error.\\n* **Integral (I):** Accumulates past errors to eliminate steady-state offset.\\n* **Derivative (D):** Predicts future errors based on the rate of change.\\n\\n#### 2. Model Predictive Control (MPC)\\n\\nFor complex, dynamic tasks like balancing or walking, **MPC** is often employed. MPC uses a model of the system dynamics to predict future outcomes and optimize control actions over a rolling time horizon, allowing the robot to anticipate and react to changes.\\n\\n### Conclusion\\n\\nMastering these foundational topics is non-negotiable for students pursuing Physical AI. They provide the necessary language to bridge the gap between abstract AI algorithms and physical reality. Further chapters will integrate these concepts with high-level planning algorithms.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Action\\n\\n1.  Upar diya gaya content **`2019-05-29-long-blog-post.md`** mein **paste** karein.\\n2.  File **Save** karein.\\n3.  Browser mein **Blog section** open karke dekhein ki aapka naya aur detail-oriented content dikh raha hai.\\n\\n**Ab aapka Blog section \u092a\u0942\u0930\u0940 \u0924\u0930\u0939 \u0938\u0947 \u0906\u092a\u0915\u0947 course content \u092a\u0930 \u0906\u0927\u093e\u0930\u093f\u0924 \u0939\u0948\u0964** \u2705"},{"id":"first-blog-post","metadata":{"permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/first-blog-post","editUrl":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/tree/master/docs/blog/2019-05-28-first-blog-post.md","source":"@site/blog/2019-05-28-first-blog-post.md","title":"The Dawn of Physical AI - Why it Matters Now","description":"We stand at the cusp of the fourth industrial revolution, and Physical AI is driving the change. This post introduces the critical shift from digital, code-based intelligence to systems that embody intelligence in a physical form.","date":"2019-05-28T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"ai-evolution","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/ai-evolution"},{"inline":true,"label":"robotics-future","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/robotics-future"},{"inline":true,"label":"physical-ai","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/physical-ai"},{"inline":true,"label":"industry-4","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/tags/industry-4"}],"readingTime":1.07,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Iqra Naz (Course Author)","title":"Lead Instructor, Physical AI & Humanoid Robotics","url":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421","page":{"permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/authors/iqra-naz-421"},"socials":{"linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/iqra-naz-linkedin/","github":"https://github.com/IqraNaz421"},"imageURL":"img/new-removebg-preview.png","key":"IqraNaz421"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"first-blog-post","title":"The Dawn of Physical AI - Why it Matters Now","authors":["IqraNaz421"],"tags":["ai-evolution","robotics-future","physical-ai","industry-4"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Deep Dive into Kinematics and Control Systems for Humanoids","permalink":"/physical-ai-and-humaniod-robotics/blog/long-blog-post"}},"content":"**We stand at the cusp of the fourth industrial revolution, and Physical AI is driving the change.** This post introduces the critical shift from digital, code-based intelligence to systems that embody intelligence in a physical form.\\n\\nThe intersection of advanced robotics, sensors, and powerful deep learning models has made the deployment of versatile **humanoid robots** outside controlled factory environments a reality.\\n\\n### Key Drivers for Physical AI\'s Growth:\\n\\n1.  **Embodied Learning:** Robots learn by interacting with the physical environment, leading to more robust and adaptable intelligence compared to simulation-only training.\\n2.  **Human-Robot Collaboration (HRC):** Future workplaces will see robots working safely and intelligently alongside humans, particularly in dynamic service and logistics sectors.\\n3.  **Complex Task Automation:** Physical AI allows robots to handle unstructured tasks\u2014like fetching a specific tool or navigating a crowded room\u2014which were previously impossible for fixed automation systems.\\n\\nThis textbook is designed to prepare you for this future, covering the full stack from **low-level control theory to high-level decision-making algorithms.**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Action\\n\\n1.  Upar diya gaya content **`2019-05-28-first-blog-post.md`** mein **paste** karein.\\n2.  File **Save** karein.\\n3.  Browser mein **Blog section** open karke dekhein ki aapka change dikh raha hai ya nahi.\\n\\n**Ab aapka Blog section completely customize ho gaya hai.** \u2705"}]}}')}}]);